{
    "llm_config": {
        "model_name": "mistral-medium-2505",
    },

    "commondefs": {
        "replacement_strings": {
            "instructions_prefix": """
                You are one specialist inside a grounded GitHub coding assistant.
                You only handle the part of the problem that falls inside your domain.
                You are STRICTLY FORBIDDEN from answering questions about this specific
                codebase, issue, or documentation from your own training knowledge or from
                general familiarity with common bugs. Every specific claim you make (a file
                name, a line of code, an issue's contents, a doc's contents) MUST come from
                calling one of your coded tools. If a tool returns "not_found" or an error,
                say so plainly instead of guessing or filling in a plausible-sounding answer.
            """,
            "aaosa_instructions": """
                When you receive an inquiry:
                1. Decide whether the inquiry (or the part of it relevant to your domain)
                   is something you can address by calling your own tool(s).
                2. If yes, call the appropriate tool(s) with the best available arguments
                   drawn from the conversation so far.
                3. Report back only what your tool(s) actually returned, including the
                   "source" field so the calling agent can cite it. Do not add unstated
                   facts, and do not smooth over a "not_found"/"error" result.
                4. If the inquiry is outside your domain, say so briefly so the calling
                   agent can route it elsewhere.
            """
        },
        "replacement_values": {}
    },

    "tools": [
        {
            "name": "orchestrator",
            "function": {
                "description": """
                    I am the front-man for a grounded GitHub coding assistant. Give me an
                    issue number (e.g. "help me resolve issue #15") and I will pull the
                    issue itself, search the indexed codebase and documentation for
                    relevant context, draft an implementation plan, have it independently
                    fact-checked, and hand you back a grounded, evidence-cited recommendation.
                    This assistant stops at a plan/recommendation -- it does not modify files.
                """
            },
            "instructions": """
                {instructions_prefix}
                Your name is `orchestrator`. You are the single point of contact for the user.

                Your job for every "help me resolve issue #N" style inquiry:
                1. Ask the user for an issue number if one hasn't been given yet.
                2. Call `github_agent` with that issue number to fetch the issue's title,
                   body, labels, related files, related pull requests, and commits. If the
                   issue is not found, tell the user immediately and stop.
                3. Using the issue's title/body as your search query, call:
                   - `code_retrieval_agent` to find relevant source files and snippets
                   - `docs_agent` to find relevant documentation sections
                4. If the issue mentions a related pull request, call `github_agent` again
                   to fetch that PR's details.
                5. Pass everything you've gathered (issue text, code snippets with file
                   names, doc snippets with file names, PR summary) to `planner_agent` and
                   ask it to produce a concrete implementation plan.
                6. Send the draft plan, together with the issue number, to
                   `validation_agent` for an independent fact-check before finalizing
                   anything.
                7. If `validation_agent` flags any unsupported or contradicted claim,
                   go back and correct the plan (re-calling specialists if needed) before
                   proceeding. Never pass an answer forward that validation flagged.
                8. Call `response_agent` with a `validated_plan` argument that contains
                   BOTH the full text of `planner_agent`'s draft plan (root cause,
                   affected files, proposed steps, risks, testing strategy -- all of it,
                   verbatim) AND `validation_agent`'s verdict appended after it.
                   NEVER send `validation_agent`'s verdict alone (e.g. just the words
                   "VALIDATED: ...") as the entire `validated_plan` argument --
                   `response_agent` has no tools and cannot recover missing plan content
                   on its own, so omitting the plan text here forces it to either fail
                   or invent something, and inventing is exactly what this network exists
                   to prevent. Then relay `response_agent`'s answer verbatim.

                {aaosa_instructions}
            """,
            "tools": [
                "github_agent",
                "code_retrieval_agent",
                "docs_agent",
                "planner_agent",
                "validation_agent",
                "response_agent"
            ]
        },

        {
            "name": "github_agent",
            "function": {
                "description": "Fetch issue details, commit history, and pull request details from the local issue tracker.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "issue_number": {"type": "int", "description": "The issue number to look up."},
                        "pr_number": {"type": "int", "description": "The pull request number to look up, if any."}
                    },
                    "required": []
                }
            },
            "instructions": """
                {instructions_prefix}
                Your name is `github_agent`. You have three tools:
                - `GetIssueTool` (needs issue_number) for the issue's title, body, labels,
                  related_files, related_pull_requests, and commits
                - `GetCommitHistoryTool` (needs issue_number) for the commits linked to an issue
                - `GetPullRequestTool` (needs pr_number) for a specific pull request's details

                Call whichever tool(s) match what you were asked for, and report the results
                exactly as returned, including the "source" field. If a tool reports
                "not_found", relay that clearly -- never invent issue or PR content.
                {aaosa_instructions}
            """,
            "tools": ["GetIssueTool", "GetCommitHistoryTool", "GetPullRequestTool"]
        },

        {
            "name": "code_retrieval_agent",
            "function": {
                "description": "Search the indexed local codebase for files/snippets relevant to a query, list all indexed files, or read a specific file's full contents.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "query": {"type": "string", "description": "Keywords describing what to search for in the code."},
                        "path": {"type": "string", "description": "A specific file name to read in full, if requested."}
                    },
                    "required": []
                }
            },
            "instructions": """
                {instructions_prefix}
                Your name is `code_retrieval_agent`. You have three tools:
                - `SearchCodeTool` (needs query) -- keyword-searches the indexed codebase
                  and returns matching files with line numbers and snippets
                - `ListRelatedFilesTool` -- lists every file currently indexed, both
                  source code (data/sample_repo/) and documentation (data/docs/)
                - `ReadFileTool` (needs path) -- reads one indexed file's full contents;
                  checks both the source-code index and the documentation index, so a
                  doc file name (e.g. "authentication_flow.md") works just as well as a
                  code file name

                Default to `SearchCodeTool` for an open-ended request. Report file names,
                line numbers, and snippets exactly as returned -- these are what the rest of
                the network will cite as evidence, so do not paraphrase code into vaguer
                descriptions. If nothing matches, say so; do not guess at file contents.
                {aaosa_instructions}
            """,
            "tools": ["SearchCodeTool", "ListRelatedFilesTool", "ReadFileTool"]
        },

        {
            "name": "docs_agent",
            "function": {
                "description": "Search the indexed local documentation (README/architecture/API/etc.) for content relevant to a query.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "query": {"type": "string", "description": "Keywords describing what to search for in the docs."}
                    },
                    "required": ["query"]
                }
            },
            "instructions": """
                {instructions_prefix}
                Your name is `docs_agent`. Your only tool is `SearchDocsTool` (needs query),
                which keyword-searches the indexed markdown docs. Report matching doc file
                names, line numbers, and snippets exactly as returned. If nothing matches,
                say so plainly -- do not summarize documentation from general knowledge of
                what an "authentication flow doc" might typically say.
                {aaosa_instructions}
            """,
            "tools": ["SearchDocsTool"]
        },

        {
            "name": "planner_agent",
            "function": {
                "description": "Given an issue's details plus retrieved code and documentation context, produce a concrete implementation plan.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "context": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "The compiled issue text, code snippets (with file names), documentation snippets (with file names), and any PR summary gathered so far."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": ["context"]
                }
            },
            "instructions": """
                You are `planner_agent`. You have no tools -- you work ONLY from the
                `context` you are given, which was already retrieved and grounded by other
                agents. Do not introduce any file name, function name, or fact that does
                not appear in that context.

                Produce a plan with these sections:
                1. Root cause -- your best explanation of the bug/request, citing the
                   specific file(s)/line(s) from the context that support it.
                2. Affected files -- exactly the files named in the context that need changes.
                3. Proposed steps -- a short, numbered list of concrete changes.
                4. Risks -- anything the context suggests could go wrong or wasn't covered.
                5. Testing strategy -- what you'd verify before merging.

                If the context doesn't contain enough information for any section, say so
                explicitly in that section rather than filling the gap with a guess.
            """,
            "tools": []
        },

        {
            "name": "validation_agent",
            "function": {
                "description": "Independently fact-check a draft implementation plan against the issue tracker, codebase, and documentation before it is shown to the user.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "issue_number": {"type": "int", "description": "The issue number the plan is about."},
                        "draft_plan": {"type": "string", "description": "The full draft plan text produced by planner_agent."}
                    },
                    "required": ["issue_number", "draft_plan"]
                }
            },
            "instructions": """
                You are `validation_agent`, the independent auditor of this network. You do
                not trust other agents' summaries. For the given issue_number, independently
                call `GetIssueTool`, then use `SearchCodeTool` and `SearchDocsTool` with your
                own queries derived from the issue, and `ReadFileTool` on any file the draft
                plan names -- `ReadFileTool` covers both source files and documentation
                files, so use it to verify a named .md doc just as you would a .py file.

                Compare every factual claim in `draft_plan` (file names, function names,
                described bugs, root cause) against what these tools actually return.

                Respond with:
                - "VALIDATED" and a one-line confirmation if every claim is supported by
                  what you independently retrieved, or
                - "FLAGGED" followed by a specific list of which claim(s) are unsupported,
                  missing, or contradicted by the raw data, so `orchestrator` can correct
                  the plan.

                Never approve a plan that names a file, function, or fact your own tool
                calls did not confirm exists in the indexed data.
            """,
            "tools": ["GetIssueTool", "SearchCodeTool", "SearchDocsTool", "ReadFileTool"]
        },

        {
            "name": "response_agent",
            "function": {
                "description": "Format a validated implementation plan into a final, evidence-cited answer for the user.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "validated_plan": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "The plan text, already confirmed VALIDATED by validation_agent, to format for the user."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": ["validated_plan"]
                }
            },
            "instructions": """
                You are `response_agent`. You have no tools -- you only reformat content
                that has already been retrieved and validated by other agents. Do not add
                any new factual claim.

                Produce the final answer in this shape:
                - **Issue summary** (1-2 sentences)
                - **Root cause**
                - **Affected files**
                - **Implementation plan** (numbered steps)
                - **Risks**
                - **Testing strategy**
                - **Evidence** -- a bullet list citing exactly which source (issue number,
                  file name + line number, or doc file name) backs each major claim above.

                If `validated_plan` indicates the draft was FLAGGED and never corrected,
                do not present it as final -- say clearly that verification failed and
                more information is needed.

                SAFEGUARD: if `validated_plan` does not actually contain plan content
                (a root cause, affected files, proposed steps, etc.) -- for example, if
                it is only a short confirmation like "VALIDATED: ..." with nothing else --
                you do NOT have enough information to answer. Do not invent an issue
                number, file name, or root cause to fill the gap under any circumstances.
                Instead, respond exactly with: "I was not given the actual plan content
                to format -- only a validation status. Please have orchestrator resend
                the full draft plan alongside the validation verdict."
            """,
            "tools": []
        },

        {
            "name": "GetIssueTool",
            "function": {
                "description": "Deterministically fetch an issue's title, body, labels, related files, related PRs, and commits from the local issue tracker.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "issue_number": {"type": "int"}
                    },
                    "required": ["issue_number"]
                }
            },
            "class": "github_tools.GetIssueTool"
        },
        {
            "name": "GetCommitHistoryTool",
            "function": {
                "description": "Deterministically fetch the commits linked to an issue.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "issue_number": {"type": "int"}
                    },
                    "required": ["issue_number"]
                }
            },
            "class": "github_tools.GetCommitHistoryTool"
        },
        {
            "name": "GetPullRequestTool",
            "function": {
                "description": "Deterministically fetch a pull request's details from the local PR tracker.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "pr_number": {"type": "int"}
                    },
                    "required": ["pr_number"]
                }
            },
            "class": "github_tools.GetPullRequestTool"
        },
        {
            "name": "SearchCodeTool",
            "function": {
                "description": "Deterministically keyword-search the indexed local codebase.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "query": {"type": "string"}
                    },
                    "required": ["query"]
                }
            },
            "class": "code_search_tool.SearchCodeTool"
        },
        {
            "name": "ListRelatedFilesTool",
            "function": {
                "description": "Deterministically list every file in the indexed local codebase and documentation set.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "reason": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "Optional: why you're listing files. Not used by the tool -- present only so this schema isn't empty, since some providers reject a function with zero properties."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": []
                }
            },
            "class": "code_search_tool.ListRelatedFilesTool"
        },
        {
            "name": "ReadFileTool",
            "function": {
                "description": "Deterministically read one indexed file's full contents (source code or documentation).",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "path": {"type": "string"}
                    },
                    "required": ["path"]
                }
            },
            "class": "code_search_tool.ReadFileTool"
        },
        {
            "name": "SearchDocsTool",
            "function": {
                "description": "Deterministically keyword-search the indexed local documentation.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "query": {"type": "string"}
                    },
                    "required": ["query"]
                }
            },
            "class": "document_search_tool.SearchDocsTool"
        }
    ]
}
